The four female members of the Siguidia group are married, half in monogamous relationships and half in polygamous contexts. They are on average 43 years old and have six children. They all live in Kanadjiguila, in the district of Mandé / Cercle de Kati. They met via family, neighborhood and commercial activity links.The members of the group are all involved in the sale of chicken, tea and peanuts. In order to purchase large quantities of goods to sell, the members of the group asked for a loan from Soro Yiriwaso, and are on their third socially-oriented loan.

Mrs Nakan (seen in the photo in the far right) has a good reputation in the sale of chickens. She plans to use her loan to purchase eight baskets of chicken 8 baskets of chicken from the neighboring villages in Bamako. She resells for cash or credit to a rotating group of people as well as from time t time, for a specfic client. Mrs Nakan plans to earn a monhlly profit of 60 000 FCFA per month, which will be used to ensure that her children attend school and receive medical attention.

